\int \frac{\sqrt{1+x}}{x}
\sqrt{1+x} = u \implies 1+x = u^2 \implies dx = 2u du
I = \int \dfrac{\sqrt{1+x}}x dx = \int \dfrac{u}{u^2-1} 2u du = 2 \int \dfrac{u^2}{u^2-1} du = 2 \int \left(1 + \dfrac1{u^2-1}\right) du
I = 2u + \int \dfrac{du}{u-1} - \int \dfrac{du}{u+1} + c = 2 u + \ln \left(\left \vert \dfrac{u-1}{u+1} \right \vert\right) + \text{constant}
\displaystyle \int\frac{2u^2}{u^2-1}\,du
2+\frac{2}{u^2-1}
1+x = t^2
